  "prompt": "What's the origin of the expression \"Yippee Ki-Yay\"?",
  "response": "The expression \"Yippee Ki-Yay\" is often associated with Western cowboy culture and has roots in old cowboy and rodeo lingo. It gained widespread popularity due to its use in popular culture, notably in the \"Die Hard\" film series where Bruce Willis's character, John McClane, uses the phrase.\n\nThe phrase itself is a playful exclamation, similar to \"Yippee\" or \"Yeehaw,\" which expresses excitement or enthusiasm. \"Ki-Yay\" doesn't have a specific meaning but serves to enhance the rhythmic and jovial nature of the expression.\n\nOver time, \"Yippee Ki-Yay\" became a catchphrase and is frequently used to convey a sense of carefree exuberance or defiance.",
